WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.720
Let's go a step deeper.

2
00:00:02.720 --> 00:00:08.480
In the first chapter, we calculated full cost for the buy options at the small number of quoted production volumes.

3
00:00:08.480 --> 00:00:11.760
These data points could be used to drive supply chain decisions,

4
00:00:11.760 --> 00:00:15.680
but what if our production estimates don’t match the quoted volumes?

5
00:00:15.680 --> 00:00:15.680


6
00:00:15.680 --> 00:00:15.680


7
00:00:15.680 --> 00:00:20.440
As Mike Tyson once said "Everyone has a plan until they get punched in the mouth."

8
00:00:20.440 --> 00:00:20.440


9
00:00:20.440 --> 00:00:20.440


10
00:00:20.440 --> 00:00:24.560
In reality, it is unlikely to order exactly the number of products that were quoted.

11
00:00:24.560 --> 00:00:28.680
Projects start with assumptions that often change as the team learns more.

12
00:00:28.680 --> 00:00:28.680


13
00:00:28.680 --> 00:00:29.640


14
00:00:29.640 --> 00:00:34.840
That is why it is important to have a tool that guides decisions over a wider range of volumes.

15
00:00:34.840 --> 00:00:37.600
Determining production volumes for a new product is full of

16
00:00:37.600 --> 00:00:43.440
uncertainty so our tool needs to help us analyze our volumes more dynamically.

17
00:00:43.440 --> 00:00:43.440


18
00:00:43.440 --> 00:00:43.440


19
00:00:43.440 --> 00:00:47.800
The primary source of uncertainty for production volumes is demand.

20
00:00:47.800 --> 00:00:50.680
This is especially true for new products.

21
00:00:50.680 --> 00:00:50.680


22
00:00:50.680 --> 00:00:50.680


23
00:00:50.680 --> 00:00:55.840
If a product has never been on the market before, how can we know how many customers will want to buy it?

24
00:00:55.840 --> 00:00:59.720
Even if your company is launching a next generation of an old product, there is

25
00:00:59.720 --> 00:01:06.360
still uncertainty based on product-market fit, outside economic conditions, and price.

26
00:01:06.360 --> 00:01:06.360


27
00:01:06.360 --> 00:01:06.360


28
00:01:06.360 --> 00:01:11.560
Demand forecasting is a fascinating and extensive topic that will not be covered in this course.

29
00:01:11.560 --> 00:01:15.720
The interdependence between price, demand, production volume and production

30
00:01:15.720 --> 00:01:20.800
cost only increases the value of a dynamic supply chain decision-making tool.

31
00:01:20.800 --> 00:01:20.800


32
00:01:20.800 --> 00:01:21.640


33
00:01:21.640 --> 00:01:24.360
You might be wondering, if we find out we need to assess another

34
00:01:24.360 --> 00:01:27.760
production volume, why don’t we just ask our suppliers for another quote?

35
00:01:27.760 --> 00:01:27.760


36
00:01:27.760 --> 00:01:27.760


37
00:01:27.760 --> 00:01:32.400
While it is a great idea to have open lines of communication with your supply

38
00:01:32.400 --> 00:01:37.920
chain, asking for quotes and preparing quotes can be time consuming for both sides.

39
00:01:37.920 --> 00:01:40.920
The minimum turn-around time for production quotes can often be

40
00:01:40.920 --> 00:01:46.440
several valuable days or even longer, which can cause unwanted project delays.

41
00:01:46.440 --> 00:01:46.440


42
00:01:46.440 --> 00:01:46.440


43
00:01:46.440 --> 00:01:50.920
Thankfully, quotes are typically set up in a way that allows for us to develop a

44
00:01:50.920 --> 00:01:56.120
scenario analysis tool to analyze volumes that were not expressly included in the quotes.

45
00:01:56.120 --> 00:01:56.120


46
00:01:56.120 --> 00:01:57.000


47
00:01:57.000 --> 00:01:59.760
Recall that the volume column is the minimum production

48
00:01:59.760 --> 00:02:03.520
volume associated with the unit cost and the non-recurring expense.

49
00:02:03.520 --> 00:02:08.240
That means the full cost formula holds between quoted production volumes.

50
00:02:08.240 --> 00:02:09.200


51
00:02:09.200 --> 00:02:09.200


52
00:02:09.200 --> 00:02:15.280
We can utilize Power BI’s Parameter function to set up a Scenario Volume Analysis.

53
00:02:15.280 --> 00:02:15.280


54
00:02:15.280 --> 00:02:15.280


55
00:02:15.280 --> 00:02:21.920
As a reminder, a Power BI parameter is a value that the user can control using a slicer.

56
00:02:21.920 --> 00:02:27.680
The parameter can be referenced in DAX measures that will update on the report as the user changes the parameter value.

57
00:02:27.680 --> 00:02:27.680


58
00:02:27.680 --> 00:02:27.680


59
00:02:27.680 --> 00:02:34.760
In the first chapter, you created a column that calculated the full cost for each row in the Quotes table.

60
00:02:34.760 --> 00:02:34.760


61
00:02:34.760 --> 00:02:34.760


62
00:02:34.760 --> 00:02:39.160
In this chapter, you will create a Full Cost measure based on the Scenario Volume parameter.

63
00:02:39.160 --> 00:02:43.680
For each part number- scenario volume combination, there may

64
00:02:43.680 --> 00:02:47.440
be many potential rows of unit cost and non-recurring expenses.

65
00:02:47.440 --> 00:02:47.440


66
00:02:47.440 --> 00:02:48.320


67
00:02:48.320 --> 00:02:51.640
We want the full cost measure to return the lowest full

68
00:02:51.640 --> 00:02:55.800
cost from the eligible supplier, part and volume combinations.

69
00:02:55.800 --> 00:02:55.800


70
00:02:55.800 --> 00:02:55.800


71
00:02:55.800 --> 00:03:00.120
This is the perfect use case for an iterative function.

72
00:03:00.120 --> 00:03:04.400
As a reminder, an iterative function is a function that iterates through all

73
00:03:04.400 --> 00:03:09.320
rows of the given table, applies the expression, and then aggregates the result.

74
00:03:09.320 --> 00:03:09.320


75
00:03:09.320 --> 00:03:09.320


76
00:03:09.320 --> 00:03:16.200
MINX returns the minimum value of an expression computed for each row of the table you pass it.

77
00:03:16.200 --> 00:03:16.200


78
00:03:16.200 --> 00:03:16.200


79
00:03:16.200 --> 00:03:22.880
In this case, we will want to utilize the MINX function because we are looking for the minimum full cost value.

80
00:03:22.880 --> 00:03:26.920
You can pass a filtered table to the iterative function, and

81
00:03:26.920 --> 00:03:29.760
it will only iterate over the rows that meet the filter criteria.

82
00:03:29.760 --> 00:03:29.760


83
00:03:29.760 --> 00:03:29.760


84
00:03:29.760 --> 00:03:35.200
This will be useful to make sure full cost is only calculated for valid quote rows.

85
00:03:35.200 --> 00:03:35.200


86
00:03:35.200 --> 00:03:35.200


87
00:03:35.200 --> 00:03:37.000
What do you know?

88
00:03:37.000 --> 00:03:42.640
The project manager says that a recent viral internet trend has affected our projected production volumes.

89
00:03:42.640 --> 00:03:47.760
Let's create a tool to help us consider the scenarios!

